There are several ways to center a `div` element using CSS. Here are some common methods:

**Method 1: Using margin and auto**

HTML:
```html
<div id="myDiv">Centered!</div>
```
CSS:
```css
#myDiv {
  width: 300px; /* set the width of the div */
  height: 200px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```
This method sets the `margin` property to `0` on both the left and right sides, and then uses the `auto` value to automatically set the margin to the center of the containing element.

**Method 2: Using flexbox**

HTML:
```html
<div id="myDiv">Centered!</div>
```
CSS:
```css
#myDiv {
  width: 300px; /* set the width of the div */
  height: 200px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
}
```
This method uses the `display` property to set the element as a flex container, and then sets the `justify-content` and `align-items` properties to `center`.

**Method 3: Using grid**

HTML:
```html
<div id="myDiv">Centered!</div>
```
CSS:
```css
#myDiv {
  width: 300px; /* set the width of the div */
  height: 200px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
}
```
This method uses the `display` property to set the element as a grid container, and then sets the `place-items` property to `center`.

**Method 4: Using absolute positioning**

HTML:
```html
<div id="myDiv">Centered!</div>
```
CSS:
```css
#myDiv {
  width: 300px; /* set the width of the div */
  height: 200px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
  position: absolute;
  left: 50%;
  top: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```
This method sets the `position` property to `absolute`, and then uses the `left`, `top`, and `transform` properties to center the element.

